"Marx A., Mast M., Knoche R., Kunstmann H.","Global climate change and regional impact on the water balance - Case study in the German alpine area [Globaler Klimawandel und Regionale Auswirkungen auf den Wasserhaushalt - Fallstudie Chiemgau-Inn-Salzach-Berchtesgadener Land]",2008,"WasserWirtschaft","98","9",,"12","16",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-53849101050&partnerID=40&md5=1776d37cb338bfba7879b5bb77ef24b2","Forschungszentrum Karlsruhe GmbH, Institut für Meteorologie und Klimaforschung (IMK-IFU), Kreuzeckbahnstr. 19, 82467 Garmisch-Partenkirchen, Germany","Marx, A., Forschungszentrum Karlsruhe GmbH, Institut für Meteorologie und Klimaforschung (IMK-IFU), Kreuzeckbahnstr. 19, 82467 Garmisch-Partenkirchen, Germany; Mast, M., Forschungszentrum Karlsruhe GmbH, Institut für Meteorologie und Klimaforschung (IMK-IFU), Kreuzeckbahnstr. 19, 82467 Garmisch-Partenkirchen, Germany; Knoche, R., Forschungszentrum Karlsruhe GmbH, Institut für Meteorologie und Klimaforschung (IMK-IFU), Kreuzeckbahnstr. 19, 82467 Garmisch-Partenkirchen, Germany; Kunstmann, H., Forschungszentrum Karlsruhe GmbH, Institut für Meteorologie und Klimaforschung (IMK-IFU), Kreuzeckbahnstr. 19, 82467 Garmisch-Partenkirchen, Germany","A quantification and possible effects of climate change on the water cycle for a German alpine and pre-alpine region have been performed using regional climate simulations. It showed out that temperature rises around 3°C until the end of this century with a maximum in the mountainous area. Mean precipitation only slightly increases. The intensities of hourly precipitation events increase dramatically which involve more intense small scale flash flood events. Daily precipitation sums also rise in future times which causes mainly large scale flooding events. For the summer months June to August, a 30 % reduction of precipitation was simulated. In combination with increasing temperatures, the total amount of usable water is expected to reduce. The risk of droughts also increases due to longer lasting and more intense dry periods.",,"alpine environment; climate change; climate modeling; drought; flash flood; global climate; hydrological cycle; mountain environment; precipitation intensity; quantitative analysis; water budget; Central Europe; Eurasia; Europe; Germany",,,,,,"(2007) (HRSG.): Climate Change 2007: The Scientific Basis, , Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change IPCC, Cambridge University Press; Grell, G., Dudhia, J., Stauffer, D., (1994) A Description of the Fifth-Generation Penn State/NCAR Mesoscale Model (MM5). NCAR Technical Note, NCAR/TN-398+STR; Jung, G., Kunstmann, H., High-Resolution Regional Climate Modelling for the Volta Basin of West Africa (2007) Journal of Geophysical Research, p. 112; Kotlarski, S., Block, A., Böhm, U., Jacob, D., Keuler, K., Knoche, R., Rechid, D., Walter, A., Regional climate model simulations as input for hydrological applications: Evaluation of uncertainties (2005) Advances in Geosciences, 5, pp. 119-125. , S; Byun, H.R., Wilhite, D.A., Objective Quantification of Drought Severity and Duration (1999) Journal of Climate, 9 (12), pp. 2747-2756. , S; Schulla, J., Jasper, K., Model Description WaSiM-ETH (2007) Technischer Report; Kunstmann, H., Schneider, K., Forkel, R., Knoche, R., Impact Analysis of Climate Change for an Alpine Catchment Using High Resolution Dynamic Downscaling of ECHAM 4 Time Slices (2004) Hydrology and Earth System Sciences, 6 (8), pp. 1030-1044. , S","Marx, A.; Forschungszentrum Karlsruhe GmbH, Institut für Meteorologie und Klimaforschung (IMK-IFU), Kreuzeckbahnstr. 19, 82467 Garmisch-Partenkirchen, Germany; email: andreas.marx@imk.fzk.de",,,,,,,,00430978,,,,"German","WasserWirtschaft",Article,Scopus,2-s2.0-53849101050
